Certainly! Below is the JavaScript function converted from your bookmarklet. The function is named `postToWordpress` and it takes a single string argument `postContent`. It opens a new window or tab with the formatted URL for posting to WordPress, using the provided content.

```javascript
function postToWordpress(postContent) {
  var selectionText = postContent || '';
  var document = window.document;
  var location = document.location;

  var wordpressUrl = 'https://wordpress.com/post/paidpursuit.wordpress.com';
  var url = wordpressUrl + "?url=" + encodeURIComponent(location.href) +
                         "&title=" + encodeURIComponent(document.title) +
                         "&text=" + encodeURIComponent(selectionText) +
                         "&v=5";

  var popup = function() {
    window.open(url, "t", "toolbar=0,resizable=1,scrollbars=1,status=1,width=660,height=570") || (location.href = url);
  };

  // Firefox requires a slight delay
  if (/Firefox/.test(navigator.userAgent)) {
    setTimeout(popup, 0);
  } else {
    popup();
  }
}

// To use the function with a selected string as post content.
postToWordpress('Your selected string here.');
```

Make sure to call the `postToWordpress` function with the actual content you want to post as the argument. The function assumes you want to create a post on WordPress using the current page's URL and title, with the additional content you provide. If you are looking to make this function dynamic, such as taking the post's URL and title as parameters, you would have to modify the function accordingly.

To modify your function so that it automatically saves a draft on WordPress, you'll need to ensure that the URL used in the function corresponds to the WordPress draft saving functionality. However, the standard WordPress URL structure does not support direct draft creation via query parameters. You typically have to use the WordPress dashboard or an API call with proper authentication to auto-save a draft.

Still, I can help you with a function that will open the WordPress post editor page, where you can manually save your post as a draft. Here's how you might set up such a function:

```javascript
function postToWordpressDraft(postContent) {
  var selectionText = postContent || '';
  var document = window.document;
  var location = document.location;

  var wordpressUrl = 'https://wordpress.com/post/paidpursuit.wordpress.com';
  var url = wordpressUrl + "?text=" + encodeURIComponent(selectionText);

  var popup = function() {
    window.open(url, "t", "toolbar=0,resizable=1,scrollbars=1,status=1,width=660,height=570");
  };

  // Firefox requires a slight delay
  if (/Firefox/.test(navigator.userAgent)) {
    setTimeout(popup, 0);
  } else {
    popup();
  }
}

// To use the function with a selected string as post content.
postToWordpressDraft('Your selected string here.');
```

This code will open the WordPress new post page with the content you provided in the `postContent` variable filled out in the editor. You would then have to manually click on "Save Draft" in the WordPress post editor.

As of my last knowledge update in early 2023, directly saving a draft through a URL parameter is not possible without using the WordPress REST API or another backend method that involves authentication to interact with your WordPress site programmatically.

For automated draft saving, you would need to explore the WordPress REST API and write a function that makes authenticated POST requests to create a draft. This process typically involves Oauth or cookie authentication and is considerably more complex than opening a URL in a new window.

Creating a WordPress draft post using the WordPress.com REST API requires authentication and client-side requests cannot be made due to the CORS policy. However, for illustration purposes, here is how a function to make an API request to create a new draft post might look like. Remember, in practice, this request needs to be made from a server-side application or a platform that is CORS-compliant with proper authentication.

You'll need a WordPress.com OAuth token to use the API for authentication. Below is a conceptual example that you shouldn't use as-is for security and functionality purposes.

```javascript
function saveDraftToWordpress(postContent, oauthToken) {
  // Replace with your actual site ID or domain
  var siteId = 'your-site-id-or-domain.com';
  var apiEndpoint = `https://public-api.wordpress.com/rest/v1.1/sites/${siteId}/posts/new`;

  // Setup the API request payload
  var postData = {
    title: "Draft Title", // Put your desired post title here
    content: postContent,
    status: 'draft' // This ensures the post is saved as a draft
  };

  // Prepare the XMLHttpRequest
  var xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();
  xhr.open('POST', apiEndpoint, true);
  xhr.setRequestHeader('Authorization', 'Bearer ' + oauthToken);
  xhr.setRequestHeader('Content-Type', 'application/json');
  xhr.onreadystatechange = function() {
    if (xhr.readyState === 4) { // Done
      if (xhr.status === 201) { // Created
        console.log('Draft saved:', JSON.parse(xhr.responseText));
      } else {
        console.error('Error saving draft:', xhr.responseText);
      }
    }
  };

  // Send the API request
  xhr.send(JSON.stringify(postData));
}

// To use the function, you must pass in the desired post content and a valid OAuth token.
saveDraftToWordpress('Your post content here', 'YourOAuthToken');
```

When using the WordPress API:

1. You need to replace `your-site-id-or-domain.com` with the actual domain name or site ID of your WordPress blog.
2. Use the actual title for the draft post you want to save.
3. Replace `'YourOAuthToken'` with your actual OAuth token. Obtaining this token involves registering an application with WordPress.com, directing the user to a login screen, and receiving the token after they have authenticated.

Due to the sensitive nature of OAuth tokens which grant access to your WordPress account, you should handle them securely and never expose them in client-side code (like JavaScript running in the browser). Typically, operations like this should be executed server-side, making sure all credentials are kept secure.

Remember that you will need to abide by WordPress.com's API documentation and guidelines, and also handle authorization properly for your use case.

Certainly! Below is an example of how you might structure the POST request to exchange an authorization code for an access token with the WordPress.com OAuth2 API, using JavaScript with the Fetch API syntax instead of a `curl` command. This example is assuming you're running from a server-side environment due to the use of `client_secret`.

```javascript
// These values should be replaced with your actual credentials and code
const clientId = 'your_client_id';
const redirectUri = 'your_redirect_uri';
const clientSecret = 'your_client_secret';
const code = 'your_received_authorization_code';

// URL endpoint for WordPress OAuth service
const oauthTokenUrl = 'https://public-api.wordpress.com/oauth2/token';

// Form data with the required parameters
const formData = new URLSearchParams();
formData.append('client_id', clientId);
formData.append('redirect_uri', redirectUri);
formData.append('client_secret', clientSecret);
formData.append('code', code);
formData.append('grant_type', 'authorization_code');

// POST request options
const requestOptions = {
  method: 'POST',
  headers: {
    'Content-Type': 'application/x-www-form-urlencoded',
  },
  body: formData,
};

// Execute the POST request
fetch(oauthTokenUrl, requestOptions)
  .then(response => response.json())
  .then(data => {
    console.log('Access Token:', data.access_token);
    // Perform further actions with the access token
  })
  .catch((error) => {
    console.error('Error fetching access token:', error);
  });
```
Keep in mind that if you're using Node.js, you'd need to use a package like `node-fetch` to make this code work, as the Fetch API is not natively available in Node.js environments.

Additionally, because handling `client_secret` on client-facing code (like in browsers) poses a security risk, the above code should only be executed in a secure server-side environment. Never expose sensitive credentials on the client side.
